{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"486e805a-342e-4811-9768-35b374fdc539","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates these:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. They contain the stack trace, exception type, and faulting address.\n\n2. **Core dumps** — if enabled:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited   # enable before running\n   ```\n   Cores land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can inspect with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./YourApp -c /cores/core.12345\n   ```\n\n3. **Console.app** → search \"Crash Reports\" for a GUI view of the `.ips` files.\n\n**Tip:** Apple crash reports are almost always available even without `createdump`, and they include enough info (signal, faulting thread, register state) to start diagnosing most NativeAOT crashes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c6e83040-8d5f-4f1b-9832-7c22087eea17","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":301,"requestId":"7646:34F832:19753C1:1D05563:69FE921A"},"id":"3b72afca-2540-4b14-88ee-c0f616ec5c0e","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:47:15.457Z","parentId":"2cffaf9c-3980-4b8f-b704-1a22f5fcb2a6"}
